rdf:Description.rdfs:label: slots
rdf:Description.skos:definition: list of slot names that are applicable to a class. slots are by default inherited over is_a and mixins.
modification date of the source of the schema. Supplied by the loader
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: source_file_date
slot_definitions
rdf:Description.skos:definition: collection of slot definitions in a schema
A class or interface
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: ClassDefinition

rdf:Description.skos:definition: Schema version
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: version
apply_to
rdf:Description.skos:definition: Used to extend an existing class definition. For example, if we have a core schema where a gene has two slots for identifier and symbol, and we have a specialized schema for my_organism where we wish to add a slot systematic_name, we can avoid subclassing by defining a class gene_my_organism, adding the slot to this class, and then adding an apply_to pointing to the gene class. The new slot will be 'injected into' the gene class.

rdf:Description.rdfs:label: SchemaDefinition
rdf:Description.skos:definition: A collection of definitions

rdf:Description.rdfs:label: required
rdf:Description.skos:definition: If true slot must have at least one value
list of class or slot definitions that are combined to create the union class
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: slot_definition_union_of
class_definition_is_a
rdf:Description.skos:definition: specifies single-inheritance between classes and slots. While multiple inheritance is not allowed, mixins can be provided effectively providing the same thing. The semantics are the same when translated to formalisms that allow MI (e.g. RDFS/OWL). When translating to a SI framework (e.g. java classes, python classes) then is_a is used. When translating a framework without polymorphism (e.g. json-schema, solr document schema) then is_a and mixins are recursively unfolded

A name to be assigned to the slot in implementations that is different that its type. The primary use for this is to allow class AND schema definitions to both have "slots" where one inline and the other a reference
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: alias
flags
rdf:Description.skos:definition: State information and other details
If true slot can have many values
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: multivalued
local_name
rdf:Description.skos:definition: the nsname (sans ':' for a given prefix)

rdf:Description.rdfs:label: prefix_uri
rdf:Description.skos:definition: A URI associated with a given prefix
The combination of is_a plus defining slots form a genus-differentia definition, or the set of necessary and sufficient conditions that can be transformed into an OWL equivalence axiom
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: defining_slots
union_of
rdf:Description.skos:definition: list of class or slot definitions that are combined to create the union class
Version of the metamodel used to load the schema. Supplied by the loader
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: metamodel_version

rdf:Description.skos:definition: id of the schema that the element was derived from. Supplied by the loader.

rdf:Description.skos:definition: specifies single-inheritance between classes and slots. While multiple inheritance is not allowed, mixins can be provided effectively providing the same thing. The semantics are the same when translated to formalisms that allow MI (e.g. RDFS/OWL). When translating to a SI framework (e.g. java classes, python classes) then is_a is used. When translating a framework without polymorphism (e.g. json-schema, solr document schema) then is_a and mixins are recursively unfolded
classes defined in schema

local_names

default and base prefix -- used for ':' identifiers, @base and @vocab
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: default_prefix
inlined
rdf:Description.skos:definition: if true then the value of this slot is inlined (i.e. a nested object) rather linked by key

rdf:Description.rdfs:label: slot_usage
rdf:Description.skos:definition: Additional info on how a slot is used in the context of a class. Many slots may be re-used across different classes, but the meaning of the slot may be refined by context. For example, a generic association model may use slots subject/predicate/object with generic semantics and minimal constraints. When this is subclasses, e.g. to disease-phenotype associations then slot_usage may specify both local naming (e.g. subject=disease) and local constraints
root of all described things
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Element
